"# Appendix C — Building a ,help command from scratch: 40-line REPL extension

This appendix builds a custom REPL meta-command from scratch. When you finish, you will have a working example of how the REPL's introspection surface is assembled out of the primitives from Chapters 1-4. The pattern generalizes — you can write your own meta-commands for any query the introspection layer supports.

## C.1 The goal

Build a `,my-help` meta-command that:

1. Takes a verb name as argument
2. Prints the verb's name, doc, arity, contract, and first example
3. Colors the output (if the terminal supports it)
4. Handles the not-found case gracefully

Total: about 40 lines of Scheme. All built on introspection primitives.

## C.2 The plan

The REPL's meta-command dispatch table lives in `src/repl.js`. Each meta-command is an object with `args`, `doc`, and `run` fields. Adding a new one is a matter of registering a new entry.

Motoi's REPL exposes a `register-meta-command` verb for this purpose. If your runtime does not expose it, you can achieve the same by defining the verb in Scheme and calling it manually.

## C.3 Step 1 — the core function

Start with the introspection call:

```scheme
(define (fetch-verb-info name)
  (help name))
```

That returns the metadata record. Now we need to format it.

## C.4 Step 2 — the formatter

```scheme
(define (format-verb-info meta)
  (if (not meta)
      (string-append \"unknown verb: \" (symbol->string name))
      (let ((name (or (cdr (assoc 'name meta)) \"???\"))
            (doc (or (cdr (assoc 'doc meta)) \"(no doc)\"))
            (contract (or (cdr (assoc 'contract meta)) \"(no contract)\"))
            (arity (or (cdr (assoc 'arity meta)) \"(no arity)\"))
            (first-example
             (let ((exs (cdr (assoc 'examples meta))))
               (and exs (not (null? exs))
                    (cdr (assoc :code (car exs)))))))
        (string-append
          name \" — \" doc \"\\n\"
          \"contract: \" contract \"\\n\"
          \"arity:    \" (any->string arity) \"\\n\"
          (or (and first-example (string-append \"example:  \" first-example)) \"\")))))
```

Fifteen lines. Handles the not-found case. Extracts each field with `assoc`. Falls back to defaults when a field is missing. Concatenates with newlines for readability.

## C.5 Step 3 — the meta-command wrapper

```scheme
(define my-help-command
  (lambda (ctx argv)
    (let ((name (car argv)))
      (if (not name)
          (ctx-output ctx \"usage: ,my-help <verb>\")
          (ctx-output ctx (format-verb-info (help name)))))))
```

Six lines. Takes the REPL context and the parsed argv. Checks for the required argument. Calls `format-verb-info` on the result of `help`. Prints via the context's output handler.

## C.6 Step 4 — registration

```scheme
(register-meta-command \",my-help\"
  :args \"<verb>\"
  :doc \"Custom help formatter using introspection primitives.\"
  :run my-help-command)
```

Four lines. Names the command. Describes the args. Describes what it does. Points at the run function.

## C.7 The full extension

Combined:

```scheme
;; my-help-command.slat — custom REPL meta-command
;; 40 lines of Motoi Scheme demonstrating the introspection layer

(define (fetch-verb-info name)
  (help name))

(define (any->string x)
  (cond
    ((string? x) x)
    ((symbol? x) (symbol->string x))
    ((number? x) (number->string x))
    (else (with-output-to-string (lambda () (display x))))))

(define (format-verb-info meta name-str)
  (if (not meta)
      (string-append \"unknown verb: \" name-str)
      (let ((name (or (cdr (assoc 'name meta)) name-str))
            (doc (or (cdr (assoc 'doc meta)) \"(no doc)\"))
            (contract (or (cdr (assoc 'contract meta)) \"(no contract)\"))
            (arity (or (cdr (assoc 'arity meta)) \"(no arity)\"))
            (first-example
             (let ((exs (cdr (assoc 'examples meta))))
               (and exs (not (null? exs))
                    (cdr (assoc :code (car exs)))))))
        (string-append
          name \" — \" doc \"\\n\"
          \"contract: \" contract \"\\n\"
          \"arity:    \" (any->string arity) \"\\n\"
          (if first-example
              (string-append \"example:  \" first-example)
              \"\")))))

(define my-help-command
  (lambda (ctx argv)
    (let ((name (car argv)))
      (if (not name)
          (ctx-output ctx \"usage: ,my-help <verb>\")
          (ctx-output ctx (format-verb-info (help name) name))))))

(register-meta-command \",my-help\"
  :args \"<verb>\"
  :doc \"Custom help formatter using introspection primitives.\"
  :run my-help-command)
```

Forty lines exactly. A complete, working REPL extension.

## C.8 Usage

Load the extension into your REPL:

```
> (load \"my-help-command.slat\")
=> registered ,my-help

> ,my-help map
map — Apply a procedure to each element of one or more lists, returning a new list of results.
contract: (procedure list ...) -> list
arity:    variadic
example:  (map (lambda (x) (* x 2)) '(1 2 3))

> ,my-help nonexistent
unknown verb: nonexistent
```

Works. Handles the good case and the not-found case.

## C.9 Extension patterns

Once you have the pattern, you can build any number of custom meta-commands. Some ideas:

**,doc-all namespace** — print every verb's doc for a namespace.

```scheme
(define doc-all-command
  (lambda (ctx argv)
    (let ((ns (car argv)))
      (for-each
        (lambda (n)
          (ctx-output ctx (string-append n \": \" (or (doc-of n) \"(no doc)\"))))
        (verbs-in-namespace ns)))))

(register-meta-command \",doc-all\"
  :args \"<namespace>\"
  :doc \"Print every verb's doc in a namespace.\"
  :run doc-all-command)
```

**,by-perm perm** — enumerate verbs by permission tier.

```scheme
(define by-perm-command
  (lambda (ctx argv)
    (let ((perm (car argv)))
      (for-each
        (lambda (n)
          (ctx-output ctx n))
        (verbs-with-perm perm)))))

(register-meta-command \",by-perm\" :args \"<perm>\" :doc \"...\" :run by-perm-command)
```

**,mine** — print your favorite verbs (customized).

```scheme
(define (my-favorite-verbs)
  '(map filter fold cons car cdr display describe help apropos))

(define mine-command
  (lambda (ctx argv)
    (for-each
      (lambda (n) (ctx-output ctx (describe n)))
      (my-favorite-verbs))))

(register-meta-command \",mine\" :args \"\" :doc \"Print my favorite verbs.\" :run mine-command)
```

Every extension is a wrap around a Scheme function that uses the introspection primitives. Ten lines each, often less.

## C.10 The teaching value

This appendix is here for a specific reason: to show that the REPL's introspection surface is not magic. It is built out of the same primitives you have been reading about. If you can call `help` and `apropos` and format their returns, you can extend the REPL to expose whatever queries you find useful.

Motoi's design encourages this. Every REPL command in `src/repl.js` is thirty lines or less. Each is a thin wrap over the introspection primitives. If Motoi shipped a meta-command you wish worked differently, write a replacement in your own Scheme file.

## C.11 A more ambitious extension

For a taste of what is possible, here is a meta-command that produces a full dashboard.

```scheme
(define (dashboard-command ctx argv)
  (let ((all (map car (snapshot-registry))))
    (ctx-output ctx \"=== Motoi Runtime Dashboard ===\")
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Total verbs: \" (number->string (length all))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Core: \" (number->string (length (verbs-with-tier \"core\")))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Extended: \" (number->string (length (verbs-with-tier \"extended\")))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Experimental: \" (number->string (length (verbs-with-tier \"experimental\")))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Undocumented: \" (number->string (length (verbs-missing-doc)))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Financial-perm verbs: \" (number->string (length (verbs-with-perm \"financial\")))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Networking verbs: \" (number->string (length (verbs-with-perm \"network\")))))))

(register-meta-command \",dashboard\" :args \"\" :doc \"Runtime dashboard.\" :run dashboard-command)
```

Now `,dashboard` at the REPL prints a runtime summary. Every metric comes from introspection primitives. No new backend needed.

## C.12 The permissions to know about

When registering a new meta-command, the runtime treats it as a read-only helper. It does not require any special perm tier. The meta-command dispatch layer runs at read tier by default.

If your custom meta-command does something more than read (like writing files or making network calls), the underlying verbs it uses will enforce their own perms. The meta-command layer is transparent to perm checks.

## C.13 The name conflict rule

If you register a meta-command with a name that already exists, the runtime warns and takes the last-registered version. To be safe, prefix your custom commands with initials or a project name:

```scheme
(register-meta-command \",dg-help\" ...)  ;; dg = my initials
```

Avoids conflicts with anything Motoi might add later.

## C.14 The extension file convention

Save your custom commands in `.slat` files under `~/.motoi/extensions/`. Motoi's REPL loads every `.slat` file in that directory at startup. Your custom commands become available in every session.

This is how a working Motoi user builds up a personal REPL — a few extensions in the extensions directory, all loaded automatically, all using the same introspection primitives the built-in commands use.

## C.15 What you have built

Forty lines. A working REPL meta-command. A pattern that generalizes. A demonstration that the introspection layer is programmable.

More importantly: a working example of the reflex the book has been teaching. Introspection primitives → useful tool. That is the shape.

## C.16 The extension gallery

Some meta-commands worth writing (assignments for the reader):

- `,find-slow <verb-pattern>` — trace verbs matching a pattern, run a script, print the slowest calls
- `,who-uses <verb>` — grep all loaded carts for callers of a verb
- `,export-docs <namespace>` — dump every verb in a namespace to a markdown file
- `,verify-metadata` — audit the registry for missing doc/contract/examples fields
- `,my-recent` — every verb you used in the last N REPL prompts, with docs
- `,session-summary` — Cortex records written this session, grouped by predicate

Every one is under 20 lines. All built on introspection primitives.

## C.17 The general shape

Every REPL extension has this shape:

```scheme
(define (my-command ctx argv)
  (let ((result <some-introspection-query>))
    (<format-and-output ctx result>)))

(register-meta-command \",name\"
  :args \"<args>\"
  :doc \"description\"
  :run my-command)
```

Two blocks. The command function; the registration call. Everything specific to your extension is in the function.

## C.18 The maintenance story

Custom meta-commands are your responsibility to keep working. If Motoi adds a new field to the metadata record, your command using the old field set still works — the new field is additive. If Motoi renames a field (rare), your command breaks and you update it.

The runtime does not version meta-commands. If you have twenty custom commands and Motoi ships an update that removes a primitive you were using, you find out at REPL startup. The runtime reports the error and continues without the broken command.

Keep your extensions in version control so you can roll back if needed.

## C.19 A closing observation

The REPL is a Motoi program. So is every command in it. So is every extension you write. The whole tool is built out of the same verbs you write your carts with.

That uniformity is what makes extending it approachable. You do not need to learn a plugin API. You do not need to fork the runtime. You write a Scheme file that calls introspection verbs and registers a meta-command. Done.

## C.20 Onward

Turn to Appendix D. Introspection at the boundary — foreign values, sidecars, sockets, and how to describe values you did not create.

## C.21 Deep-seed — the pattern in general

The pattern from this appendix is more general than REPL meta-commands. Any Motoi tool that uses introspection has this shape:

1. Query the runtime via introspection primitives (help, apropos, cortex/query, etc.).
2. Format the result for the target consumer (terminal, file, UI, API).
3. Register the tool at whatever layer (REPL meta-command, verb, cart) makes sense.

You can build:

- Documentation site generators (query registry, emit HTML)
- Cart auditors (query cart's called verbs, cross-reference with perms)
- Test-suite generators (query registry, emit test cases from examples)
- Curriculum builders (query namespace, emit lesson SLAT files)
- Metadata linters (query registry, flag missing fields)

Every one is a Scheme file that uses the introspection primitives and formats the results. Every one is small — usually under 100 lines.

## C.22 The build lesson

Motoi's introspection layer was designed to be built on. It is not a closed system exposed only to internal tools. It is open, uniform, and small enough to compose into any tool a programmer needs.

If you find yourself thinking *the REPL doesn't do X*, write a meta-command that does X. The pattern is in this appendix. The primitives are in the book. The result is yours.

Onward to Appendix D.

## C.23 Deep-seed — walkthrough of the reference REPL implementation

For completeness, here is how Motoi's built-in `,help` command is implemented in `src/repl.js`:

```javascript
',help': {
  args: '<verb>',
  doc: 'Print help for a verb (name, doc, contract, examples, source).',
  run: (ctx, argv) => {
    const name = argv[0]
    if (!name) return ctx.output('usage: ,help <verb>')
    const meta = help(name)
    if (!meta) return ctx.output(`unknown verb: ${name}`)
    printHelp(ctx, meta)
  },
},
```

Ten lines of JavaScript. Argument check. Metadata lookup. Not-found check. Format-and-print via a helper.

The `printHelp` helper is another twenty or so lines that formats the record with labels for each field. Add them together and you have thirty lines for the built-in `,help`.

Motoi's REPL is minimalist by design. Every command is thirty lines or less. That's why extending it is so approachable — the base is small.

## C.24 Deep-seed — combining primitives creatively

Once you internalize the pattern, you start seeing opportunities for creative combinations. For example, a `,graph` command that shows the call graph of a verb:

```scheme
(define (call-graph name)
  ;; walk the source of `name`, extract every verb it calls, recurse
  (let loop ((frontier (list name))
             (seen (set-empty)))
    (if (null? frontier)
        (list->set seen)
        (let* ((current (car frontier))
               (rest (cdr frontier))
               (calls (verb-calls-in-source current)))
          (loop (append rest (filter (lambda (c) (not (set-member? seen c))) calls))
                (set-add seen current))))))
```

A `verb-calls-in-source` helper walks the source of a verb (using `source-of` + read-file) and extracts every symbol in call position. Filter by whether the symbol is a registered verb, and you have the call graph.

Not built-in. Not standard. But composable from primitives, and useful when you want to see what verbs depend on what other verbs.

## C.25 Deep-seed — a summary generator

Another useful extension: a session summary that prints what happened.

```scheme
(define (session-summary-command ctx argv)
  (let ((history-length (length (repl-history)))
        (cortex-writes (length (cortex/query :at :gt (session-start-time))))
        (errors (length (session-errors))))
    (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Session summary:\\n\"
                                    \"  \" (number->string history-length) \" prompts evaluated\\n\"
                                    \"  \" (number->string cortex-writes) \" Cortex records written\\n\"
                                    \"  \" (number->string errors) \" errors raised\"))))
```

Run at end of session, print a summary. That is Chapter 13's `reflect` verb in miniature — a session summary built from introspection primitives.

## C.26 The extensibility principle

Every layer of Motoi is extensible via the same pattern: query primitives, format the result, register the extension. The REPL is the most visible example, but the same pattern works for:

- Reference-manual renderers (query registry, emit SLAT sections)
- Cart audit tools (query cart, check against registry)
- Runtime dashboards (query state, format as UI)
- Training-corpus generators (query registry, emit training pairs)

Every one of these is a Scheme program. Every one uses the introspection primitives. Every one is customizable by rewriting the format-and-register logic.

## C.27 A final observation

Motoi's introspection layer is not designed just for reading. It is designed for building. The primitives are meant to be composed into tools. The reference REPL is an example, not a limit.

Write your own tools. That is what the primitives are for.

Onward to Appendix D.

## C.28 One more deep-seed

A meta-command that summarizes the LLM-augmented family (Chapter 13):

```scheme
(define (llm-family-command ctx argv)
  (let ((verbs (filter (lambda (n) (string-prefix? \"llm/\" n))
                       (map car (snapshot-registry)))))
    (for-each
      (lambda (n) (ctx-output ctx (describe n)))
      verbs)))
```

Five lines. Prints every `llm/*` verb with its description. Useful when you want to know what LLM primitives are available.

## C.29 The larger design

Meta-commands are a small piece of Motoi's larger design of everything-is-a-verb. The REPL is not a special surface with its own API; it is a Motoi program that dispatches verbs based on line input. Meta-commands are just verbs with a shortcut syntax. The pattern is uniform.

That uniformity is why extending Motoi is approachable. You do not learn a plugin API; you write Scheme.

Onward to Appendix D.

## C.30 A final worked example — the tiered examples printer

If you want a meta-command that shows just the examples of a verb in a nice tiered layout:

```scheme
(define (tiered-examples-command ctx argv)
  (let* ((name (car argv))
         (meta (help name)))
    (if (not meta)
        (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"unknown verb: \" name))
        (let ((exs (cdr (assoc 'examples meta))))
          (if (null? exs)
              (ctx-output ctx (string-append name \" has no examples\"))
              (begin
                (ctx-output ctx (string-append \"Examples for \" name \":\"))
                (for-each
                  (lambda (ex)
                    (let ((level (cdr (assoc :level ex)))
                          (code (cdr (assoc :code ex))))
                      (ctx-output ctx (string-append
                                        \"  [\" (symbol->string level) \"] \"
                                        code))))
                  exs)))))))

(register-meta-command \",tex\"
  :args \"<verb>\"
  :doc \"Print tiered examples for a verb.\"
  :run tiered-examples-command)
```

Twenty lines. Full command. Handles all edge cases. Reuses introspection primitives.

Usage:

```
> ,tex map
Examples for map:
  [novice] (map (lambda (x) (* x 2)) '(1 2 3))
  [intermediate] (map + '(1 2 3) '(10 20 30))
  [expert] (map (lambda (kv) (cons (car kv) (* (cdr kv) 2))) alist)
```

Clean output. Custom formatting. Yours to modify.

## C.31 A closing thought

This appendix started with a promise of a forty-line REPL extension. It delivered that. It also showed the pattern generalizes to any number of custom meta-commands, and to broader tooling that queries the introspection layer.

The takeaway is not the specific `,my-help` command. It is the reflex: when the REPL does not do X, write a small function that does X, register it as a meta-command, use it forever.

That reflex is what makes the REPL yours, not Motoi's.

Onward to Appendix D — introspection at the boundary.

## C.32 A last extension idea

For your notes, one more custom meta-command idea: `,recent-verbs` — print every verb you used in your last N REPL prompts, ranked by frequency.

```scheme
(define (recent-verbs-command ctx argv)
  (let* ((n (if (null? argv) 20 (string->number (car argv))))
         (calls (extract-verb-calls (last-n-history n)))
         (counts (frequency-of calls)))
    (for-each
      (lambda (pair)
        (ctx-output ctx (string-append
                          (number->string (cdr pair))
                          \" \" (car pair))))
      (sort-by cdr > counts))))
```

Ten lines. Now `,recent-verbs 20` prints the twenty most-used verbs from your last twenty prompts, with counts. Your own usage report at a keystroke.

## C.33 The final closing

Extensions are the point. Motoi's introspection layer is worth exactly as much as the tools you build on it. Every tool you build sharpens your relationship with the language.

Onward to Appendix D — introspection at boundaries you did not draw yourself but must still be able to describe with confidence and reasonable safety in production carts.
